AGI - The Women's Centre against the violence of Aosta reports in a note of having received reports from women "who, coming in public health offices of the regional territory to access the voluntary interruption of pregnancy, have been in the same places subjected to undue interference and pressure from volunteers, consisting in imposing listening to the fetal beat or in the promise of economic support or consumer goods, with the precise intent of choosing them.
"The Women's Centre, in synergy with the Antiviolence Centres belonging to the national network Di.Re - Women on the net against violence - continues the widespread communication also on social channels - will therefore start actions of monitoring the correct application of law 194/1978 in the regional territory, and actions of sensitization and resistance, supporting women and evaluating with them, if they recognize the conditions and in respect of their will, any useful initiative to protect them.
&nbsp;
The Women's Centre shares, in fact, the concerns expressed in the choice of the Government to provide, with an amendment to Law 194, the possibility for consultors, public reception and protection of women's health, to agree the presence of so-called pro-life associations, not only in support of the difficult maternity paths after birth, but also in the delicate phase of ripening of the decision to interrupt, or not, pregnancy. The legislative choice to authorize the use, at this stage, in the presence of third-sector entities that ideologically fight for the abolition of the law on voluntary termination of pregnancy, brings with it the concrete risk of victimization due to the exercise of psychological pressure on women, as demonstrated by the cases also occurring in the Aosta Valley".&nbsp;
<h2>Chairman Centre Aosta:"Pressions on women rising"</h2>
"The pressures not to make abortions have always been but have increased since this government is there and since the rule, now approved, which allows anti-abortionist associations to be present in consultors." Anna Ventriglia, president of the Women's Centre against the Violence of Val d'Aosta, has been active for 25 years. "Our fear is that with the 'legalization' of these pressures they increase even more conditioning towards women. Sometimes they consist of only promising help in buying milk and diapers, as if this could affect such a delicate choice." Ventriglia claims that she cannot enter "in the detail of the stories that are covered by the anonymity but I can say that the women who come to us are grieving and express a great discomfort for how their right is questioned".

