AGI - A blood test managed to predict osteoarthritis of the knee at least eight years before the revealing signs of the disease appeared on X-rays. It reveals a study conducted by researchers from Duke Health, in the journal Science Advances. Researchers have validated the accuracy of blood test, which identifies key osteoarthritis biomarkers and have shown that the test is able to predict the development of the disease and its progression. The research proposes blood examination as superior to current diagnostic tools, which often do not identify the disease until it has caused structural damage to the articulation.
&nbsp;
"Today, in order to have a clear evidence of knee osteoarthritis, an X-ray is needed and, when this occurs at X-rays, the disease has already progressed for a long time - said Virginia Byers Kraus, professor at the departments of Medicine, Pathology and Orthopedic Surgery of Duke University School of Medicine and senior author of the study - our blood test shows that it is possible to detect this disease much earlier than is currently."
&nbsp;
osteoarthritis, or OA, is the most common form of arthritis and is estimated to affect 35 million adults in the United States, causing a significant economic and social impact. Currently there is no cure, but the success of potential new therapies could depend on the early identification of the disease and the slowing down of its progression before it becomes debilitating. Kraus and colleagues focused on the development of molecular biomarkers that can be used both for clinical diagnostic purposes, and as a research tool to promote the development of effective drugs.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
In previous studies, the blood biomarkers test showed an accuracy of 74% in predicting knee OA progression and 85% in knee OA diagnosis. The current study further refined the predictive capabilities of the test. Using a large UK database, researchers analyzed the serum of 200 white women, half diagnosed with OA and the other half without the disease, combined with body mass index and age. Scientists discovered that a small number of biomarkers present in the blood test could distinguish women with OA of the knee from those without, seizing the molecular signals of the OA eight years before many of the women were diagnosed with an X-ray.
&nbsp;
"This result is important because it provides further evidence of the existence of abnormalities in the articulation that can be detected by blood biomarkers long before X-rays can detect OA - said Kraus - osteoarthritis in early stage could provide a 'will end of opportunity including stopping the course of the disease and restoring the health of articulation". &nbsp;

